vin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice de Neville was born in 1269. She married Thomas de Grey. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1315, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1269–1315":"1269–1315","1266–1310":"1266–1310","1283–1310":"1283–1310","1285–1344":"1285–1344","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","28 Jul 1310":"28. juuli 1310","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1266":"1266","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","Castle Heaton, Northumberland, England":"Castle Heaton, Northumberland, England","Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Heton, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1269–1315":"1269–1315","1266–1310":"1266–1310","1283–1310":"1283–1310","1285–1344":"1285–1344","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","28 Jul 1310":"28. heinäkuuta 1310","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1266":"1266","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","Castle Heaton, Northumberland, England":"Castle Heaton, Northumberland, England","Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Heton, Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"f